tool.name: CalculateTreeHeightFromPoints

param.name: inputTreePts
param.dialogReference: Input existing tree points without height information.

param.name: idField
param.dialogReference: Select the Unique ID field within the tree feature class, such as TreeFID.

param.name: calcBaseHeight
param.dialogReference: Select this option to calculate the base elevation of the tree points - where they intersect with the ground surface, or DTM.

param.name: inputGroundDTM
param.dialogReference: The input bare-earth Digital Terrain Model (DTM) raster. The elevation values contained in this raster will be used to vertically align the trees with the ground surface.

param.name: calcTreeHeight
param.dialogReference: Select to calculate the maximum tree height and add it as an attribute value.

param.name: inputNDSM
param.dialogReference:
The input normalized Digital Surface Model (nDSM) raster. The nDSM is calculated by subtracting the bare-earth terrain model from the surface model (DSM - DTM = nDSM), and represents a continous "height above ground" surface. These surfaces are easily calculated using classified LiDAR data.

The nDSM raster is used to calculate the maximum height value using zonal statistics, after a small buffer is applied to the tree points.

param.name: inputHeight
param.dialogReference: Select a minimum tree height value. Trees with heights smaller than this value will be removed from the output. (Default is 5 units.)

param.name: bufferDistance
param.dialogReference:
The buffer distance, in native units, applied to the input points and used in the tree height calculation. This will ensure a sufficient sample of nDSM pixels to determine the maximum height near the tree point.

Note: the appropriate value will depend on your tree size & spacing, raster resolution, and point accuracy.

param.name: overwriteExistingHeights
param.dialogReference: Select this option to overwrite any existing height values in the input tree features.

tool.summary:
Calculates tree height values for input tree point features. Two raster inputs are needed: a bare-earth Digital Terrain Model (DTM) is used to determine the tree base elevation (the intersection with the ground surface), and a normalized Digital Surface Model (nDSM) is used to determine maximum tree height.

Once base elevation and height values are available, accurate 3D tree models can easily be generated:
tool.usage: Input tree points are buffered by a user-specified value, then maximum height values are calculated using zonal statistics. The ouput tree points, with heights, can be loaded directly into the 3D Cities Information Model (3DCIM) geodatabase.
